+# GitHub setup guide (beginner friendly)
+
+This guide walks you through creating a GitHub account, creating a repository, and connecting your local project to GitHub.
+
+## 1. Create a GitHub account
+
+1. Go to https://github.com.
+2. Click **Sign up**.
+3. Follow the prompts to create your account.
+
+## 2. Install Git on your computer
+
+Git is the tool that lets your computer talk to GitHub.
+
+### macOS
+
+1. Open **Terminal** (search for Terminal in Spotlight).
+2. Run:
+   ```bash
+   git --version
+   ```
+3. If prompted to install Xcode Command Line Tools, approve it.
+
+### Windows
+
+1. Download Git from https://git-scm.com/download/win.
+2. Run the installer and keep the default options.
+3. Open **Git Bash** and run:
+   ```bash
+   git --version
+   ```
+
+### Linux (Ubuntu/Debian)
+
+1. Open **Terminal**.
+2. Run:
+   ```bash
+   sudo apt update
+   sudo apt install git
+   git --version
+   ```
+
+## 3. Configure Git (one-time setup)
+
+Replace the placeholders with your name and email:
+
+```bash
+git config --global user.name "Your Name"
+git config --global user.email "you@example.com"
+```
+
+## 4. Create a new repository on GitHub
+
+1. Log in to GitHub.
+2. Click **New** (or the **+** menu in the top-right).
+3. Name the repository (for example: `plane-spotter`).
+4. Choose **Public** or **Private**.
+5. Click **Create repository**.
+
+## 5. Connect your local project to GitHub
+
+Open a terminal **in your project folder**, then run:
+
+```bash
+git init
+git add .
+git commit -m "Initial commit"
+```
+
+Then connect to GitHub (replace `<YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME>` and `<REPO_NAME>`):
+
+```bash
+git branch -M main
+git remote add origin https://github.com/<YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME>/<REPO_NAME>.git
+git push -u origin main
+```
+
+## 6. Common day-to-day workflow
+
+When you make changes:
+
+```bash
+git add .
+git commit -m "Describe your change"
+git push
+```
+
+## 7. Keep secrets out of GitHub
+
+If your web app needs API keys (for example, an aviation data API), keep them in a `.env` file that you do **not** commit.
+
+1. Create a `.env` file:
+   ```bash
+   touch .env
+   ```
+2. Add your keys:
+   ```bash
+   AVIATION_API_KEY=your-key-here
+   ```
+3. Create a `.gitignore` file (or add to it):
+   ```bash
+   echo ".env" >> .gitignore
+   ```
+
+## 8. Helpful next steps for your app
+
+- Sketch what information you want to show for each plane (flight number, origin, altitude, airline, etc.).
+- Decide whether you want a map view or a list view.
+- Look into flight data providers (for example OpenSky Network or ADS-B Exchange) and read their usage policies.
+
+If you get stuck, share the exact error message and the command you ran—copy/paste is perfect.
 
EOF
)
